<DOC><DOCNO> AP890802-0174 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2132EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     08-02 0389</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador,0399</SECOND><HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Attack Towns</HEAD><BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas foughtovernight battles with government soldiers on San Salvador'snorthern outskirts, and others attacked at least four townsWednesday.   Six people were reported killed and more than 10 wounded in thetowns. At least one soldier and a civilian were killed and threepeople were wounded in the battles Tuesday night in San Ramon andMejicanos, working-class areas on the city's northern edge.   Venceremos, the guerrilla radio station, said the attacks ontowns were part of a rebel campaign against ``the fascistgovernment'' of President Alfredo Cristiani and ``increases intransportation costs and repression in general.''   Cristiani's conservative administration lifted price controls onabout 200 consumer items and services earlier this week, includingtransportation and electricity, in an effort to revive thewar-battered economy.   Bus fares increased Wednesday, in some cases to almost doubletheir former levels. New electricity rates will be announced nextweek.   Guerrillas of the rebel Farabundo Marti National LiberationFront has fought U.S.-supported governments for a decade. Humanrights groups say more than 70,000 people have been killed, most ofthem civilians.   Several rebel columns attacked military positions at San PedroNonualco, 38 miles east of the capital, early Wednesday and onecivilian was killed in the fighting, the army press office said.   A Venceremos broadcast told people to stay off the road in thearea because rebel forces had mined it.   One rebel was killed and five were wounded in a guerrilla attackon military positions in northern Chalatenango province, near theHonduran border, and other rebel forces attacked San Jorge andCarolina in San Miguel, an eastern province, the army said. Therewere no reports on casualties in San Jorge and Carolina.   Sgt. Ventura Lopez, who commands a squad of 10 soldiers in theSan Ramon district, one of the areas of overnight fighting, saidhis post was attacked by about 60 rebels from the San Salvadorvolcano northeast of the city.   He said the guerrilas, armed with dynamite, assault rifles androcket-propelled grenades, were driven off by about 100 soldiersfrom the Belloso infantry battalion.   It was the fifth rebel attack in eight months on the San Ramonarmy post. About 200 guerrillas are believed to be camped on thevolcano.</TEXT></DOC>